Type conversion is the process of changing a value from one data type to another.

**Two types of conversion:**

1. **Implicit (Coercion)** - JavaScript automatically converts types
2. **Explicit** - You manually convert using functions

```javascript
// Implicit conversion
let result = "5" - 3;  // 2 (string becomes number)

// Explicit conversion
let num = Number("5");  // 5
```

// Using String() constructor
String(42)      // "42"
String(true)    // "true"
String(null)    // "null"

// Using .toString() method
(42).toString()     // "42"
(3.14).toString()   // "3.14"

// Using template literals (modern way!)
const age = 25;
`I am ${age} years old`  // "I am 25 years old"

// Addition with string
"5" + 3      // "53" (number becomes string!)

// Subtraction with string
"5" - 3      // 2 (string becomes number)

// Comparison
5 == "5"     // true (loose equality converts)
5 === "5"    // false (strict equality, no conversion)

// Logical operators
"hello" && 42    // 42 (returns last truthy)
0 || "default"   // "default" (returns first truthy)

